      work: "Gītā-bhāṣya",
      locus: "2.55",
      sanskrit: "gamanādipravṛttirnātyabhisandhipūrvikā mattādipravṛttivaditi ‘yā niśā’ ityādinā darśayiṣyan lakṣaṇaṃ prathamata āha – prajāhātīti| evaṃ paramānandatṛptaḥ kimarthamevaṃ pravṛttiṃ karotīti praśnābhiprāyaḥ| prārabdhakarmaṇeṣattirohita brahmaṇo vāsanayā prāyo'lpābhisandhipravṛttiḥ sambhavatītyāśayavān pariharati| prāyaḥ sarvān prajahāti| śukādīnāmapīṣaddarśanāt| ‘tvatpādabhaktimicchanti jñāninastatvadarśinaḥ’ ityuktestāmicchanti| yadā tvindrādīnāmāgraho dṛśyate tada'bhibhūtaṃ teṣāṃ jñānam| taccoktam – ‘ adhikārikapuṃsāṃ tu bṛhatkarmatvakāraṇāt| udbhavābhibhavau jñāne tato'nyebhyo vilakṣaṇāḥ ’ iti ata eva vailakṣaṇyādanadhikāriṇāmāgrahādi cedasti na te jñānina ityavagantavyam| na cātra samādhiṃ kurvato lakṣaṇamucyate| ‘yaḥ sarvatrānabhisnehaḥ’ iti snehaniṣedhāt | nahi samādhiṃ kurvatastasya śubhāśubhaprāptirasti| asamprajñātasamādheḥ | samprajñāte tvavirodhaḥ| tathā'pi na tatraiveti niyamaḥ| kāmādayo na jāyante hyapi vikṣiptacetasām| jñānināṃ jñānanirdhūtamalānāṃ devasaṃśrayāt ’ iti smṛteḥ| manogatā hi kāmāḥ| atastatraiva tadviruddhajñānotpāttau yuktaṃ hānaṃ teṣāmiti darśayati -manogatāniti| virodhaścocyate ‘raso'pyasya paraṃ dṛṣṭvānivartate’ iti| na caitadadṛṣṭvā'phalapanīyam| puruṣavaiśeṣyāt| ātmanā paramātmanā| paramātmanyeva sthitaḥ san| ātmākhye tasmin sthitasya tatprasādādeva tuṣṭirbhavati| ‘ viṣayāṃstu parityajya rāme sthitimatastataḥ| devādbhavati vaituṣṭirnānyathā tu kathañcana ‘ iti nārāyaṇarāmakalpe ’ |ato nātmā jīvaḥ",
      ourRendering: "His movement and other activity is not preceded by strong deliberate intent, like the activity of a madman and so on — intending to show this by ‘yā niśā’ later, He first states the mark by ‘prajahāti’. The drift of the question: being thus satisfied in supreme bliss, why does he engage in activity at all? With the intent that, for one whose Brahman is slightly veiled by commenced (prārabdha) karma, an activity with little deliberate intent generally arises through latent impressions, He resolves it. He abandons ‘almost’ all — for even in Śuka and the rest a little is seen; since it is said, ‘The knowers, the seers of truth, desire devotion to your feet’, they desire that. Where insistence is seen in Indra and the others, there their knowledge is overcome. As stated: ‘In men of office, by reason of their great karmic load, knowledge arises and is overcome; therein they differ from others.’ Hence, by such difference, if there be insistence and the like in the unqualified, they should be known as not knowers. Nor is the mark here being stated of one engaged in samādhi, since by ‘he who is unattached everywhere’ attachment is denied; for one engaged in samādhi there is no encountering of good or ill — that being unconscious samādhi; in the conscious samādhi there is no contradiction, yet there is no rule that it be only there. As the smṛti says, ‘Desires and the rest do not arise even in the distracted-minded knowers, whose impurities are burnt away by knowledge, through resort to the Lord.’ Desires are indeed mind-seated; hence, when in that very mind a knowledge opposed to them arises, their relinquishment is fitting — He shows this by ‘mano-gatān’. The opposition is stated: ‘his relish too turns away on seeing the Supreme.’ And this is not to be explained away as fruitless without that seeing, because of the distinction among persons. ‘By the Self’ means by the Supreme Self; established in the Supreme Self alone; for one established in That called the Self, contentment arises from His grace alone, as in the Nārāyaṇa-Rāma-kalpa: ‘Having given up the objects, for one established in Rāma, contentment comes from the Lord and in no other way whatsoever.’ Therefore the self is not the individual soul.",
