      sanskrit: "prasādam adhigacchatīty uktaṃ tatra prasāde sati kiṃ syād ity ucyate prasāda iti | cittasya prasāde svacchatva-rūpe sati sarva-duḥkhānām ādhyātmikādīnām ajñāna-vilasitānāṃ hānir vināśo 'sya yater upajāyate | hi yasmāt prasanna-cetaso yater āśu śīghram eva buddhir brahmātmaikyākārā paryavatiṣṭhate pari samantād avatiṣṭhate sthirā bhavati viparīta-bhāvanādi-pratibandhābhāvāt | tataś ca prasāde sati buddhi-paryavasthānaṃ tatas tad-virodhy-ajñāna-nivṛttiḥ | tatas tat-kārya-sakala-duḥkha-hānir iti krame 'pi prasāde yatrādhikyāya sarva-duḥkha-hāni-karatva-kathanam iti na virodhaḥ ||65||",
      ourRendering: "It was said ‘he attains serenity’; now what comes to be when serenity exists is stated by ‘prasāde’. When there is serenity of the mind, of the form of limpidity, there arises for that ascetic the destruction, the cessation, of all his sorrows — the personal and the rest, the play of ignorance. For, of the serene-minded ascetic, the understanding of the form of the unity of Brahman and Self quickly, swiftly, comes to abide all around, becomes firm, since the obstacle of contrary conviction and the like is absent. And thence: when serenity exists there is the standing-firm of the understanding; thence the cessation of the ignorance opposed to it; thence the destruction of all its effect, sorrow — even in this sequence, in serenity, the statement that it is a destroyer of all sorrow, for the sake of magnifying it, is no contradiction.",
      source: "data/sources/sanskrit/vedanta/gretil_bhg4comm_ch2.txt (GRETIL: gretil/1_sanskr/2_epic/mbh/ext/bhg4c02u.htm)"
