      locus: "2.66",
      sanskrit: "nāsti na vidyate na bhavatīty arthaḥ, buddhiḥ ātma-svarūpa-viṣayā ayuktasya asamāhitāntaḥ-karaṇasya | na ca asti ayuktasya bhāvanā ātma-jñānābhiniveśaḥ | tathā -- na cāsty abhāvayata ātma-jñānābhiniveśam akurvataḥ śāntir upaśamaḥ | aśāntasya kutaḥ sukham ? indriyāṇāṃ hi viṣaya-sevā-tṛṣṇātaḥ nivṛttir yā tat-sukham, na viṣaya-viṣayā tṛṣṇā | duḥkham eva hi sā | na tṛṣṇāyāṃ satyāṃ sukhasya gandha-mātram apy upapadyate ity arthaḥ",
      ourRendering: "There is not, does not exist, does not come to be — that is the meaning — the understanding whose object is the nature of the Self, for the unsteadied one, whose inner organ is uncomposed. Nor is there, for the unsteadied one, ‘contemplation’ (bhāvanā), the intent dwelling on Self-knowledge. Likewise: nor for the non-contemplating one, who does not make the intent dwelling on Self-knowledge, is there ‘peace’, calm. For the unpeaceful one, whence pleasure? That which is the turning-away of the senses from the thirst for the service of objects — that is pleasure; not the thirst whose object is objects, for that is verily pain. While thirst exists, not even a whiff of pleasure is possible — that is the meaning.",
      source: "data/sources/sanskrit/vedanta/shankara_gita_bhasya.txt (GRETIL: gretil/1_sanskr/6_sastra/3_phil/vedanta/bhgsbh_u.htm)"
