      sanskrit: "imam evārthaṃ vyatireka-mukhena draḍhayati nāstīti | ayuktasyājita-cittasya buddhir ātma-viṣayā śravaṇa-mananākhya-vedānta-vicāra-janyā nāsti notpadyate | tad-buddhy-abhāve na cāyuktasya bhāvanā nididhyāsanātmikā vijātīya-pratyayānantaritasajātīya-pratyaya-pravāha-rūpā | sarvatra naño 'stīty anenānvayaḥ | na cābhāvayata ātmānaṃ śāntiḥ sakāryāvidyā-nivṛtti-rūpā vedānta-vākya-janyā brahmātmaikya-sākṣāt-kṛtiḥ | aśāntasyātma-sākṣātkāra-śūnyasya kutaḥ sukhaṃ mokṣānanda ity arthaḥ ||66||",
      ourRendering: "This very point He strengthens by way of the negative, by ‘nāsti’. For the unsteadied one, of unconquered mind, the understanding whose object is the Self, born of the Vedānta-inquiry called hearing and reflection, ‘is not’, does not arise. In the absence of that understanding, ‘nor for the unsteadied one is there contemplation’, of the nature of meditation (nididhyāsana), of the form of an unbroken flow of homogeneous cognition uninterrupted by heterogeneous cognition — the construction is with ‘there is not’ throughout. ‘Nor for the non-contemplating one’ of the Self is there ‘peace’, of the form of the cessation of ignorance together with its effect, the direct realization of the unity of Brahman and Self born of the Vedānta-sentences. For the unpeaceful one, void of Self-realization, ‘whence pleasure’, the bliss of liberation — that is the meaning.",
      source: "data/sources/sanskrit/vedanta/gretil_bhg4comm_ch2.txt (GRETIL: gretil/1_sanskr/2_epic/mbh/ext/bhg4c02u.htm)"
