      work: "Subodhinī",
      locus: "2.66",
      sanskrit: "indriya-nigrahasya sthita-prajñatā-sādhanatvaṃ vyatireka-mukhenopapādayati nāstīti | ayuktasya avaśī-kṛtendriyasya nāsti buddhiḥ | śāstrācāryopadeśābhyām ātma-viṣayā buddhiḥ prajñaiva notpadyate | kutas tasyāḥ pratiṣṭhā-vārtā | kuta ity atrāha na ceti | na cāyuktasya bhāvanā dhyānam | bhāvanayā hi buddher ātmani pratiṣṭhā bhavati, sā ca ayuktasya yato nāsti | na cābhāvayataḥ ātma-dhyānam akurvataḥ śāntiḥ ātmani cittoparamaḥ | aśāntasya kutaḥ sukham mokṣānanda ity arthaḥ ||66||",
      ourRendering: "He establishes, by way of the negative, that restraint of the senses is the means to sthita-prajña-hood, by ‘nāsti’. For the unsteadied one, whose senses are unmastered, there is no understanding: the understanding whose object is the Self, the very insight, born of the teaching of scripture and teacher, does not arise. Whence the talk of its standing firm? To ‘whence’ He says ‘na ca’: nor for the unsteadied one is there contemplation, meditation; for it is by contemplation that the understanding’s firmness in the Self comes to be, and that does not exist for the unsteadied one. Nor for the non-contemplating one, who does not do meditation on the Self, is there peace, the ceasing of the mind in the Self. For the unpeaceful one, whence pleasure, the bliss of liberation — that is the meaning.",
