      sanskrit: "indriyāṇāṃ hi yasmāt caratāṃ sva-sva-viṣayeṣu pravartamānānāṃ yat mano 'nuvidhīyate anupravartate tat indriya-viṣaya-vikalpanena pravṛttaṃ mano 'sya yateḥ harati prajñām ātmānātma-vivekajāṃ nāśayati | katham ? vāyuḥ nāvam iva ambhasi udake jigamiṣatāṃ mārgāduddhṛtya unmārge yathā vāyuḥ nāvaṃ pravartayati, evam ātma-viṣayāṃ prajñāṃ hṛtvā mano viṣaya-viṣayāṃ karoti",
      ourRendering: "Of the senses ranging, engaged each in its own object — that mind which ‘follows after’, runs along after — that mind, set going by the conceptual fancy of sense-object, robs his insight, this ascetic’s, the insight born of the discrimination of Self from non-Self, destroys it. How? ‘As wind a boat on the water’: just as wind, lifting up off its course a boat of those wishing to go on the water, drives it onto a wrong course, so the mind, robbing the insight whose object is the Self, makes it an insight whose object is objects.",
      source: "data/sources/sanskrit/vedanta/shankara_gita_bhasya.txt (GRETIL: gretil/1_sanskr/6_sastra/3_phil/vedanta/bhgsbh_u.htm)"
