      ourRendering: "To ‘there is no understanding for the unsteadied one’ He gives the cause by ‘indriyāṇām’. Of the senses, unmastered, ranging at will in objects, when even one single sense the mind ‘follows after’ — mastered, goes along with that sense — then that one sense robs the insight, the understanding, of the mind or of the man, makes it scattered toward objects. How much more is to be said when many rob the insight! Just as the wind whirls about on every side the boat of a careless helmsman — so it is.",
      source: "data/sources/sanskrit/vedanta/gretil_bhg4comm_ch2.txt (GRETIL: gretil/1_sanskr/2_epic/mbh/ext/bhg4c02u.htm)"
